  "doc_id": "46490",
  "text": "Any step in the activation sequence, from control of [Ca 2ϩ ] i to contractile protein Ca 2ϩ sensitivity, might conceivably depend on muscle length. In cardiac muscle, the steepness of the steady-state length-tension relationship can be explained primarily by changes in Ca 2ϩ sensitivity, whereas the slow changes in tension developed after an alteration in length involve changes in both Ca 2ϩ supply and Ca 2ϩ sensitivity [CITATION_1] . Changes in Ca 2ϩ sensitivity are not explained by changes in the affinity of troponin C for Ca 2ϩ [CITATION_2] , which is consistent with the persistence of this phenomenon in smooth muscle. At the present time, it is unclear how many of the mechanisms in cardiac muscle (or even skeletal muscle) are relevant to smooth muscle.",
